canonical:
  title: 兜率院鍾銘幷序
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 兜率院者崇敎寺住持僧統弘闡與門下侍中邵台輔同發願所創立也院旣成門人慈尙隨發願募三百五十斤鑄置洪鍾工旣畢功屬余爲銘勤請難拒略爲之言此非敢自是也盖不得已耳銘曰耽耽精舍于水之津云誰居之惟衆侁侁或食或講或夜或晨不可戶告景鍾乃陳大簴雙植洪槌傍橫不擊則已擊則振鳴山撟海蕩鬼蹶神驚非雷非霆殷其大聲
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 兜率院鍾銘幷序
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 兜率院者。崇敎寺住持僧統弘闡與門下侍中邵台輔同發願所創立也。院旣成。門人慈尙隨發願。募三百五十斤。鑄置洪鍾。工旣畢功。屬余爲銘。勤請難拒。略爲之言。此非敢自是也。盖不得已耳。銘曰。耽耽精舍。于水之津。云誰居之。惟衆侁侁。或食或講。或夜或晨。不可戶告。景鍾乃陳。大簴雙植。洪槌傍橫。不擊則已。擊則振鳴。山撟海蕩。鬼蹶神驚。非雷非霆。殷其大聲。
korean:
  title: 도솔원종 명 병서
  author: 김부식
  language: kor
  text: 도솔원(兜率院)은 숭교사(崇敎寺)  주지(住持)  승통(僧統)  홍천(弘闡)이 문하시중(門下侍中)  소태보(邵台輔)와 함께 발원(發願)하여 창건한 것이다. 원(院)이 이미 이루어짐에 따라 문인(門人) 자상(慈尙)이 따라 발원(發願)하여 쇠[鐵] 3백 5십근을 시주(施主)들에게서 얻어서 녹여 큰 종(鍾)을 만들었다. 일이 끝나매 나에게 명(銘) 짓기를 부탁하는데 간절히 청함을 거절하기가 어려워서 몇 마디 말을 쓰게 되니 이것은 감히 잘했다는 것이 아니라 대개 마지못해서 쓴 것이다. 명에 이르기를,웅장한 정사(精舍)는 물의 가에 있도다. 뉘가 거처하는 데 인고. 여러 대중이 모여 있다. 여기에서 먹기도 하고 강경(講經)하여 밤으로도 하고 새벽으로도 한다. 밤에 자고 새벽에 일어날 시간을 방(房)마다 이르기가 어려워서 큰 종(鍾)을 달았네. 종틀은 쌍으로 세우고 큰 망치는 곁에 걸렸다. 안치면 몰라도 치게 되면 크게 울려 산이 무너질 듯 바다가 일렁거리며 귀신도 놀랜다. 우레도 아니요 벼락도 아니건만 우렁우렁 큰 소리로다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0520_040_0010&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Inscription for the Bell of Douseul Monastery, with Preface
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Douseul Monastery was founded through the joint vow of Hongchan, the chief priest and ecclesiastical administrator of Sungyo Temple, and Sho Tae-bo, an attendant minister of his congregation. When the monastery was completed, the disciple Ja-sang, following the same vow, gathered three hundred and fifty pounds of metal from donors and cast a great bell. Upon finishing this work, he entreated me to compose an inscription. His earnest plea was difficult to refuse, so I have written these humble words—not out of any pride in my work, but simply because I could not decline.

    The inscription reads:

    Solemn stands the hall of practice by the water's edge.
    Who dwells within its walls?
    The gathered multitude, intent and true.
    Some eat, some chant the sutras,
    Now through the night, now at dawn.
    But how to signal each small chamber
    When day turns dark and dawn turns dim?
    Then came the great bell, hanging high.

    Double posts stand firm beneath it,
    The massive mallet hangs beside.
    When struck, it sleeps; but strike it once—
    It wakes and roars with resonance!
    Mountains shudder at its voice,
    The seas churn into waves,
    Ghosts start back in fear,
    The spirits tremble.

    Neither thunder nor lightning's crack,
    Yet it rolls forth with such might—
    A sound immense, profound, and vast.
  footnotes:
    - Douseul Monastery (兜率院) takes its name from Tusita Heaven in Buddhist cosmology, the heaven where Maitreya, the future Buddha, dwells.
    - 'This is a practical inscription: the bell served not only a spiritual function but also a temporal one, marking the monastic schedule for the community.'
    - The vivid natural imagery of mountains, seas, and spirits reflects the Daoist-Buddhist synthesis characteristic of medieval Korean thought.
